 I gave my AI agent a task
"Monitor my Aave position. If health factor drops below 1.2  top up my collateral immediately."
Simple enough right?

Then I asked  okay but how does it actually pay for that?
The answer broke my brain.
Here's the problem nobody talks about:
Traditional payment systems were built for humans.
A human has a bank account. A human can verify their identity. A human can type in a password. A human can press confirm.
Your AI agent?
It has none of that.
Walk through this with me:
Agent detects your health factor dropping. Needs to top up collateral  fast. Opens a payment request.
Step 1 :Login required. Agent has no username.
Step 2 :2FA verification. Agent has no phone.
Step 3 :Confirm transaction. Agent is waiting for a human.
The human is asleep.
Position gets liquidated.
The agent did everything right.
Observed the risk. Made the correct decision. Initiated the action.
And still failed 
because the payment layer was built for a species that sleeps.
This isn't a small bug. It's a fundamental mismatch.
Traditional finance assumes:
Actor = Human
Identity = Government ID
Authorization = Password + OTP
Custody = Bank holds funds
Agents break every single assumption.
No identity. No OTP. No one to hold funds on behalf of. No sleep schedule that matches yours.
The worst part?
Even if you give your agent a credit card 
Who issued it? In whose name? What happens when it gets flagged for unusual activity?
An AI agent making 400 transactions at 3am looks exactly like fraud.
Because to traditional finance it basically is.
This is the exact moment I understood why blockchain exists for agents.
Not as hype. Not as speculation.
As infrastructure.
Programmable money. No middleman to call. No identity check to fail. No fraud flag to trigger.
Just  if condition is met, transaction executes.
That's it.
The payment layer is broken for autonomous agents.
And most developers building AI products haven't hit this wall yet.
Have you? 👇
